## Description {#details}

All of these cast traits are meant to be implementations for useful casts that users may want to use that are outside the standard behavior.

An example of how to use a special cast called <code>CastTrait</code> is:

template&lt;&gt; struct <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/castinfo">CastInfo&lt;foo, bar&gt;</a> : public CastTrait&lt;foo, bar&gt; &#123;&#125;;

Essentially, if your use case falls directly into one of the use cases supported by a given cast trait, simply inherit your special <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/castinfo">CastInfo</a> directly from one of these to avoid having to reimplement the boilerplate <code>isPossible/castFailed/doCast/doCastIfPossible</code>. A cast trait can also provide a subset of those functions. This cast trait just provides castFailed for the specified <code>To</code> type to make <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/castinfo">CastInfo</a> specializations more declarative. In order to use this, the target result type must be <code>To</code> and <code>To</code> must be constructible from <code>nullptr</code>.
